I was thinking about how a disorder of virtues is what makes characters in literature and film attractive. E.g. in the real world usually people who are wise tend to also be calm and silent, but a character who is a very wise and loquacious neurotic tends to be far more exciting.

Or for example in reality loyalty tends to correlate with general patience, yet a novel character who is very faithful yet short-tempered would end up beloved by readers...

"It is the appearance of inconsistency, and not its absence, that makes people attractive." - Nassim Taleb

Cosmetic plastic surgery is the industrialization of August Weissman's experiment of trying to debunk Lamarckism by cutting the tails of rats for 22 generations in a row. Treating living matter like it's dead matter, which always has this disturbing necromantic character.

The reason plastic surgery is so turbonormie-"coded" is because it runs on pre-Platonic thinking where its clientele is unable to intuit it doesn't "really" modify their inner essence and it's just a pure phenomenon without a corresponding idea in God's mind, an optical illusion.

It has to do with the way they are raised and early imprinting on their older relatives who are royalty and they begin to see life through this feudal myth prism of knights. So the Shaw quote about royalty being a sort of hallucination if uncharitable is probably not fully wrong.

Dmitry Galkovsky had an interesting theory that English super-aristocrats, the members of the ruling dynasty, live inside a feudal myth of Western European chivalry full of noble knights, lieges, selfless sacrifices, Hospitallers, etc. that twists the way they perceive the world.
